## RAP Pipeline & Dashboards

### Quick orientation

| What | Where |
|---|---|
| Project root | `~/dev/projects/liferay-release-analytics/` |
| DB | PostgreSQL `release_analytics` (local) |
| Pipeline entry | `bash run_pipeline.sh` |
| Export script | `utils/export_looker.R` (use v2 ‚Äî see below) |
| Data destination | Google Sheets ‚Üí Looker Studio |
| Two dashboards | Situation Deck (S-files) ¬∑ Landscape Report (L-files) |

### Architecture

```
Jira (LPP/LPD/Stories) ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îê
Testray                  ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚î§
lizard (CCN/NLOC)        ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚î§‚îÄ‚îÄ‚ñ∫ PostgreSQL ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚ñ∫ export_looker.R ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚ñ∫ Google Sheets ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚ñ∫ Looker Studio
git churn CSVs           ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚î§
breaking changes         ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îò
feature flags            ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚ñ∫ apply_feature_flag_dampening.R

liferay-portal checkout ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚ñ∫ evaluate_pr.sh ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚ñ∫ branch risk score (standalone)
```

### The four-layer model ‚Äî where accountability lives

A framework for evaluating any proposal to replace tooling with AI.

| Layer | Owner | Examples |
|---|---|---|
| Data (root) | Testray, CI, git, Jira | Test results, triage labels, churn, defects |
| Logic | Code / deterministic tools | Hotfix packaging, CI execution, pipeline transforms |
| Analysis & reasoning | AI / RAP | Risk scoring, flakiness detection, trend analysis |
| Judgment | Human | Triage decisions, release calls, hotfix scope |

Each layer has a distinct job. The temptation ‚Äî especially as AI becomes more capable ‚Äî is to collapse all four into a prompt. AI *feels* like it can handle data retrieval, logic execution, analysis, and judgment simultaneously. The problem is that "feels capable" and "is accountable" are different things.

When layers get collapsed:
- **Data gets skipped** ‚Äî AI reasons from training data instead of your actual test history
- **Logic gets approximated** ‚Äî AI describes what a hotfix should do instead of building what it needs to be
- **Analysis loses grounding** ‚Äî conclusions aren't traceable back to source data
- **Judgment disappears** ‚Äî decisions get made without anyone owning them

Collapsing the layers doesn't remove accountability. It just makes it invisible until something breaks.

**The loop:** Human judgment ‚Üí triage labels ‚Üí training data ‚Üí better AI reasoning ‚Üí sharper signals for the next human decision. The layers feed each other; none replaces another.

### Key tables

| Table | Grain | Key fields |
|---|---|---|
| `dim_release` | 1 per release | `release_label`, `release_date`, `is_major_release`, `is_lts`, `months_in_field`, `release_status` |
| `dim_component` | 1 per component | 240 components, 15 teams |
| `dim_module_component_map` | module ‚Üí component | join key = `module_path` ‚Üí `dim_module.module_path_full` |
| `dim_module` | 1 per module | `module_path_full`, `module_path_category` |
| `fact_forecast_input` | component √ó quarter | `churn_count`, `lpp_actual`, `lpd_actual`, `story_count`, `breaking_count`, `is_forecast_row`, `is_feature_flagged`, `churn_dampening_factor` |
| `fact_file_complexity` | file (lizard snapshot) | `avg_ccn`, `max_ccn`, `avg_nloc`, `avg_ccn_java`, `avg_ccn_frontend`, `language_mix` |
| `fact_test_quality` | test case | `routine_id` is key join field |
| `fact_triage_results` | PR √ó case | triage pipeline output: `BUG / NEEDS_REVIEW / FALSE_POSITIVE` |
| `stg_lizard_raw` | function-level staging | aggregated ‚Üí `fact_file_complexity` |

**Retired:** `fact_release_complexity` (SonarQube era)

### Composite risk scores

**Dashboard forecast (component √ó quarter):**
- `lpp_hist_score` = 60% historical bug average + 40% churn signal, normalized 0‚Äì100
- `lpd_pred` = Random Forest regression; requires `months_in_field >= 9`
- `risk_score` = `(lpp_hist_score + lpd_pct) / 2`, range 0‚Äì100
- `overall_risk` tier: Very High / High / Medium / Low / Very Low

**PR Risk Scoring Engine (standalone):**

| Signal | Weight |
|---|---|
| Code complexity (`max_ccn`) | 28% |
| Churn | 25% |
| Defects | 20% |
| Test coverage | 15% |
| Dependencies | 12% |

- `max_ccn` p95 denominator = **16 (fixed)** ‚Äî CCN capped at 100 before aggregation
- Rationale in `scoring_normalization` ‚Äî do not recalibrate silently

### Testray routine IDs ‚Äî never conflate

| Signal | Routine ID | Cadence |
|---|---|---|
| Acceptance | 590307 | Daily |
| Release | 82964 | Pre-ship |

### Dashboard file map

**Situation Deck (S-files):** P1 Bug Forecast, P2 Team Release Story, P3 Risk Heat Map, P4 Churn Trends, P5 Team Scorecard, P6 Model Notes

**Landscape Report (L-files):** P1 Severity Distribution, P2 Bug Discovery Timing, P3 Language Blind Spots, P4 Complexity & Tech Debt, P5 Topic Analysis (filter by `period`, not `year`)

### Team Release Story layout (single-page one-pager)

| Row | Content |
|---|---|
| 1 ‚Äì Headline Bar | avg_risk_score, risk tier, status |
| 2 ‚Äì Where You Stand | Landscape / Situation / Scorecard panels |
| 3 ‚Äì The Story | S01 risk heat map table |
| 4 ‚Äì Stakes/Forecast | lpp_hist_score vs lpd_pred with actuals |

